@index INDEX
@WORDWRAP


@node MAIN "SQLMan User Guide"

 @{b}SQLMan User Guide@{ub}

  Welcome to the SQLMan database managemement tool. This application based on the SQLite database
 engine and lets you create, view and modify databases. The database handling can happen via the
 GUI or there is an SQL command shell to serve any needs. There is a preliminary support for open
 xml spreadsheet files which can be converted to databases and even to native Amiga spreadsheets.
 This is a must for the Hollywood SQLite users.

 Please follow the topics below to learn more.

  @{" Requirements " link req}   What you need to use SQLMan

  @{" Licence      " link licence}   What you don't want to read

  @{" History      " link history}   Changelist

  @{" Contact      " link contact}   How to reach the author

  @{" Main window  " link mainwindow}

  @{" Menu         " link menu}


  @{b}Usage:@{ub} (these functions can be reached already, but will be detailed in the future)

	- creating a new database
	- modify content of a database
	- remove tables from a database
	- importing from excel spreadsheets
	- converting excel spreadsheet to TurboCalc
	- read Odyssey browser's saved passwords

@endnode
@node CONTACT "contact"

	Lázár Zoltán a.k.a. Lazi

	E-mail: info@kezdobetu.hu

@endnode


@node MENU "menu"

	@{b}Project@{ub}
		- New
			- File database
				Creates a new empty database file.

			- Memory database
				Creates a new empty database in memory. All data will be lost on exit.

			- Open
				Opens an SQLite database file

			- Close
				Closes the currently opened database.

			- Save as...
				(not implemented yet)

			- Import
				- Excel table XLSX
					Convert a worksheeet from a #?.xlsx spreadsheet to a database table.
					(A database should be opened/created before)

			- Export
				- XLS to TurboCalc via AREXX
					Creates a new TurboCalc spreadsheet from an already imported excel worksheet.

	@{b}SQL@{ub}
		- SQLDump
			- Translates the entire database to an SQL program and inserts into the SQL console
			  which can be used to create the same database when it is executed.

		- Load SQL file
			Loads a text file to the console.

		- Create table
			Opens the Create table window, where you can define the structure of a new table which
			can be added to the current database. Other tables will be intact.


@endnode

@node MAINWINDOW "Main Window"
 @{b}Main window@{ub}

	 +-------+-------------------+
	 |   1.  |        3.         |
	 |       |                   |
	 +-------+-------------------+
	 |   2.  |        4.         |
	 |       |                   |
	 +-------+-------------------+

  The main window has four important sections.
  The left side displays the database structure. The tables are shown in the upper part and the
  fields of the selected table is shown below it.

  1. @{" Tables " link tables}
     You can select the table by clicking on the list.

  3. @{" Fields " link fields}
     The fields of the selected table. Double click selects the sorting order of the data view.

  3. @{" Values " link data}
     Shows the data in the selected table. It loads the full table content to the list in memory,
     so large databases may take some time to load. This behaviour may be changed in the future.
     Double click enters the row values to the console.

  4. @{" Console " link console}
	 This is an SQLite console.


@endnode
@node "tables"
 @{b}Tables@{ub}

	The database is build up of independent tables. You can have many tables in one single database.
	The list is displays the table name, the number if fields and the last item of the key field.

@endnode
@node FIELDS "fields"
 @{b}Fields@{ub}

	The field list is shows the structure of the selected table. The fields have a type attribute
	wich is describes the type of the value it holds, however SQLite is very liberal to data types.

	Double left click - sets order of the query.
@endnode
@node DATA "data"
 @{b}Values@{ub}

	This listview shows the actual data in the selected table. The sortig order can be selected from
	the fields listview.
	All of the table data currently entirely loaded into memory.

	Double left click on a data record inserts an UPDATE command to the console with full parameters
	of the given record.

	e.g.: an UPDATE record from the sqltest.data database's customer table show something like this:

    UPDATE CUSTOMERS SET
	  CompanyName = "Blauer See Delikatessen",
	  ContactName = "Hanna Moos",
	  ContactTitle = "Sales Representative",
	  Address = "Forsterstr. 57",
	  City = "Mannheim",
	  Region = "",
	  PostalCode = "68306",
	  Country = "Germany",
	  Phone = "0621-08460",
	  Fax = "0621-08924"
	WHERE CustomerID = "BLAUS";

@endnode
@node CONSOLE "console"
 @{b}Console@{ub}

	This is the tricky part. You can enter any valid SQLite commands and hit the execute button.
	The effect of the commands takes place instatntly on the current database.
	Refer to an SQLite manual for commands and syntax.

	The console has four buttons:

	Dump all	- same as the SQL/SQLdump menu. Dumps the entire database as SQL commands to the console
	
	Custom dump	- (not implemented yet)
	
	Clear		- trash the entire content of the console
	
	Execute		- sends the content of the console to the SQLite engine. If an error happens the message
			  can be seen on the status bar at the bottom of the window.
@endnode




@node "req"
 @{b}Requirements @{ub}

   @{b}AmigaOS 3.x@{ub}
	
	- Kickstart 3.0 (V39)+
	- MUI 3.8 or better
	- 68020+
	- CyberGraphX or Picasso96
	- TextEditor.mcc 15.40 or better

   @{b}AmigaOS 4.x@{ub}

	- TextEditor.mcc 15.40 or better

@endnode
@node HISTORY "History"
@{b}History@{ub}

	Version 0.1 (28-Sept-14)

	- Initial alpha release to check if it is useful enough for anybody.


@endnode


